                <a class="text-dark" data-doi="10.1515/iral-2024-0165" href="/document/doi/10.1515/iral-2024-0165/html">
                    <span class="text-dark ahead-of-print-title">
<em>An accident was happened?</em> Conceptual and input biases in the overpassivization of English unaccusative verbs</span>
                </a>
            </div>
            <div class="ahead-of-print-details">
                <div class="date">
    January 21, 2025
</div>
                <div class="authors">Jieun Kim, Shinshil Han, Sang-Ki Lee</div>
                <div>
    
</div>
            </div>
        </div>
        
    </div>
    <div class="ahead-of-print-abstract-download">
        
            <button class="btn-abstract-dgb">
            
                <div class="abstract-dgb">
                    <span class="dgb-abstract-title">Abstract</span>
                    <div class="dgb-abstract-arrow"></div>
                </div>
            
            </button>
        
        

    
        
            
            
                <a class="btn-abstract-download-dgb" href="/document/doi/10.1515/iral-2024-0165/pdf">
                    <div class="abstract-dgb">
                        <span class="dgb-abstract-title">Download PDF</span>
                        <div class="dgb-download-icon"></div>
                    </div>
                </a>
            
        
    


    </div>
    <div class="article-content hidden">
        <div>
            <div class="abstract">
                
                    <div class="abstractContent">
                        The overpassivization of unaccusative verbs (e.g., An accident was happened ) has been widely observed among second language (L2) learners, regardless of their first languages. In an attempt to determine the effects of cognitive factors on overpassivization, the present study investigated how input frequency, types of alternation (i.e., unaccusatives with and without transitive counterparts), types of causation (i.e., externally and internally caused events), and the interactions among these factors affect L2 learners’ judgments of English unaccusativity. A forced-choice acceptability judgment task (AJT) was administered to 97 Korean EFL learners, utilizing 52 items based on the three factors. According to a multilevel regression model, all those factors and the three-way interaction among them significantly predicted learners’ AJT scores. Specifically, in externally caused event construals, learners demonstrated greater accuracy when exposed to high frequency and non-alternating verbs. Additionally, accurate judgments on alternating unaccusatives were associated with discourse contexts interpreted as internally caused rather than externally caused. These findings highlight the importance of considering the statistical nature of language learning, learners’ learning histories, and potential conceptual biases in explaining L2 English unaccusativity. Overall, the study sheds light on the complex interplay between linguistic input and cognitive factors in L2 acquisition processes.
                    </div>
                
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
                        </li>
                    
